NaBH4-TMEDA and a palladium catalyst as efficient regio- and chemoselective system for the hydrodehalogenation of halogenated heterocycles Giorgio Chelucci ⁎ Susanna Figus Dipartimento di Agraria, Università di Sassari, Viale Italia 39, 07100 Sassari, Italy Dipartimento di Agraria, Università di Sassari Viale Italia 39 Sassari 07100 Italy ⁎ Corresponding author. Tel.: +39 0 79 229539; fax: +39 0 79 229559. Graphical abstract The pair NaBH4-TMEDA as hydride source and a palladium catalyst in THF prove to be an efficient system for the hydrodehalogenation of halogenated heterocycles with one or more heteroatoms. In general, Pd(OAc)2-PPh3 rapidly hydrodehalogenates reactive halo-heterocycles such as bromo-pyridines, -quinolines, -thiophenes, -indoles, -imidazoles, etc., at room temperature in very good yields, whereas in most cases PdCl2(dppf) reduces less reactive halides such as chloro-pyridines, -quinolines, -pyrimidines and bromo-indoles, -benzofurans, etc. Moreover, PdCl2(tbpf) shows to be even more active removing the 2- and 5-chlorine from both thiophene and thiazole rings. The reaction conditions tolerate various functional groups, allowing highly chemoselective reactions in the presence of halide, ester, alkyne, alkene and nitrile substituents. Moreover, with a proper selection of the catalyst it is also possible to obtain a good control in the regioselective hydrodehalogenation of a variety of polyhalogenated substrates. Keywords Hydrodehalogenation Reduction Haloheterocycles Palladium catalysts Sodium borohydride N,N,N′,N′-tetramethylethylenediamine 1 Introduction The substitution of halogens from aromatic rings by hydrogen is an important chemical transformation in organic synthesis because this exchange reaction can constitute a key step in the synthesis of heteroaryl-based molecules in a number of cases: (i) a halogen substituent can serve as excellent blocking group for a reactive position of a heterocycle, thus allowing a reaction to be addressed toward a less reactive one; then, after having fulfilled its function the halogen can be removed [1,2]. (ii) In a stereodifferentiating process involving a heteroaromatic compound the presence of a halogen in the heterocyclic ring can help to increase the reaction stereoselectivity, subsequently the removal of the halogen by hydrogen can be pursued [1,3]. (iii) The conversion of a functional group (FG) bonded to a heteroaromatic ring into a halide substituent and its subsequent removal from the heterocycle can constitute a way to convert a C-FG into a C–H bond [4]. (iv) The presence of a halogen on a heterocyclic ring can activate its α-position toward specific reactions, then the halogen can be removed [5]. Finally, (v) it should be noted that often it is not possible to directly introduce a halogen on an unreactive position of a heterocycle as other more reactive free positions are halogenated more quickly; however, a solution to this problem could be the halogenation of both positions, followed by selective removal of the halogen from the more reactive one [6]. A wide variety of hydrodehalogenating systems have been developed over the years for the hydrodehalogenation of halogenated heterocycles [7]. Reduction is usually mediated by a transition-metal catalyst (Ni, Pd, Rh, Pt) and is performed with molecular hydrogen, metal hydrides or hydrogen sources such as formic acid and its salts, hydrazine, alkoxides possessing a β-hydrogen, etc. [7]. A number of hydrogenating systems has been also extended to halogenated heteroaromatics, although the application of several of them to these substrates are rather sporadic. A recent review cover this subject in some extent [6]. Most hydrodehalogenations of halogenated heterocycles are often accomplished by catalytic hydrogenation on metal catalyst, Pd/C or Raney Nickel, and halogen-metal exchange reaction [6]. These processes are often troublesome to execute since the former ignites easily and the latter requires anhydrous conditions and low reaction temperature. For safety and simplicity of operation, a liquid-phase process without using molecular hydrogen is more advantageous. Interestingly, some alternative methods have been recently described, such as (i) hydrogenolysis of aryl halides with catalytic Pd/C in the presence of hydrazine hydrochloride [8]; (ii) indium-mediated dehalogenation of haloheteroaromatics in water [9]; (iii) reduction of chloroarenes by Pd(OAc)2 in combination with polymethylhydrosiloxane and aqueous KF [10], (iv) dehalogenation of activated and unactivated aryl halides by catalytic Pd-complexes under transfer reaction conditions [11,12], (vi) deiodination [13] and dechlorination [14] with sodium formate and catalytic palladium catalysts, (vii) Fe(acac)3 catalyzed hydrodehalogenation of aryl halides with t-BuMgCl as reductant [15], and (viii) hydrodehalogenation with sodium borohydride (NaBH4) [16,17]. However, most of these methods appear limited to halopyridines, involving other halogenated heterocycles in only some well-defined cases [6]. Therefore, systematic studies addressing the application of a single hydrodehalogenating system to a wide range of halo-heterocycles, also including evidences of chemo- and regioselective reductions, are missing. In this paper, we report a complete account on the use of the pair sodium borohydride/N,N,N′,N′-tetramethylethylenediamine (NaBH4-TMEDA) under palladium catalysts as an efficient system for the hydrodehalogenation a large variety of halogenated heterocycles (Scheme 1 ) [17]. Moreover, in this circunstance we also show that this system allows both highly chemoselective hydrodehalogenation in the presence of different functional groups and good efficiency in the regioselective reduction of a variety of polyhalogenated substrates. 2 Experimental 2.1 General information All reactions were carried out under nitrogen in oven-dried glassware with magnetic stirring. Unless otherwise noted, all materials were obtained from commercial suppliers and were used without further purification. All solvents were reagent grade. THF was distilled from sodium-benzophenone ketyl and degassed thoroughly with dry nitrogen directly before use. Unless otherwise noted, organic extracts were dried with Na2SO4, filtered through a fritted glass funnel, and concentrated with a rotary evaporator (20–30mmHg). Flash chromatography was performed with silica gel (200–300 mesh) using the mobile phase indicated. Melting points are uncorrected. The NMR spectra were measured on 300 spectrometer at 300 for 1H and 75.4MHz for 13C in CDCl3 solution with TMS as an internal standard). Pd2(dba)3-DavePhos Pd2(dba)3-P(t-Bu)3 Pd2(dba)3-XantPhos and Pd(OAc)2-XPhos. Anhydrous THF (13.2mL) was degassed by bubbling argon for few minutes, then Pd(OAc)2 (7.2mg, 0.033mmol, 5mol%) and PPh3 (17.7mg, 1.132mmol, 20mol%) were added and the resulting mixture stirred at room temperature for 30min. The halogenated heterocycle (0.66mmol), TMEDA (0.130g, 1.12mmol, 1.7equiv) and finally NaBH4 (42.4mg, 1.12mmol, 1.7equiv) were introduced in sequence. The mixture was stirred at room temperature or heated at 65°C under argon for the proper time. The residue was taken up in brine and extracted with ethyl acetate. The organic phase was separated, dried, the solvent was evaporated and the residue was purified by flash chromatography (mixtures of petroleum ether and ethyl acetate) to give pure hydrodehalogenated heterocycles. 2.6.2 Procedure using preformed catalysts PdCl2(dppf), PdCl2(tbpf) and (A.caPhos)PdCl2. A mixture of the halogenated heterocycle (0.66mmol) in anhydrous THF (13.2mL) was degassed by bubbling argon for few minutes. Then, PdCl2(dppf) (27.0mg, 0.033mmol, 5.0mol%), TMEDA (0.130g, 1.12mmol, 1.7equiv) and finally NaBH4 (42.4mg, 1.12mmol, 1.7equiv) were introduced in sequence. The mixture was stirred at room temperature under argon for the proper time and then worked up as described above. 2.7 (Z)-2-bromo-3-styrylpyridine (1p) A suspension of the benzyltriphenylphosphonium bromide (0.76g, 1.75mmol), K2CO3 (2.42g, 17.50mmol), 2-bromopyridine-3-carbaldehyde (0.19g, 1.75mmol) and a few milligrams of 18-crown-6 in 50mL of anhydrous dichloromethane was refluxed for 12h. After being washed with water, the organic layer was dried on anhydrous MgSO4, filtered, and the solvent was evaporated under reduced pressure. The residue was purified by flash chromatography using petroleum ether/ethyl acetate=9:1 to give pure 1p: 0.59g (82% yield), oil; 1H NMR (400.1MHz, CDCl3): 8.22 (d, 1 H, J =4.4Hz), 7.40 (d, 1 H, J =7.6Hz), 7.22–7.17 (m, 3H), 7.14–7.09 (m, 2H), 7.02 (dd, 1 H, J =4.4, 7.6Hz), 7.90 (d, 1 H, J =12Hz), 5.40 (d, 1 H, J =12Hz). 13C NMR (100.6MHz, CDCl3): δ 148.6, 143.5, 139.0, 135.7, 135.1, 133.1, 129.0, 128.4, 127.8, 127.2, 122.4. Anal. calcd. for C13H10BrN: C, 60.02; H, 3.87; N, 5.38. Found: C, 60.66; H, 3.82; N, 5.40. 2.8 Methyl 3-bromo-1H-indole-1-carboxylate (10e) This compound was purified by flash chromatography using petroleum ether/ethyl acetate=9:1. Oil; 1H NMR (400.1MHz, CDCl3): δ 8.14 (d, 1 H, J =0.8), 7.63 (s, 1 H), 7.51 (d, 1 H, J =7.6Hz), 7.37 (dt, 1H, J =7.6, 1.2Hz), 7.31 (dt, 1 H, J =7.6, 1.2Hz), 4.01 (s, 3 H); 13C NMR (100.6MHz, CDCl3): δ 150.6, 134.5, 129.3, 125.6, 124.3, 123.5, 119.5, 115.0, 98.8, 54.0. Anal. calcd. for C10H8BrNO2: C, 47.27; H, 3.17; N, 5.51. Found: C, 47.65; H, 3.13; N, 5.56. 3 Results and discussion 3.1 Hydrodehalogenation of halogenated pyridines Starting our investigation to optimize the reaction conditions, the reductions were carried out with 2-bromo-6-phenylpyridine 1a as a model substrate. Initial experiments were performed at room temperature with an excess of the couple NaBH4-TMEDA (1.7equiv) in the presence of the inexpensive catalytic system formed by Pd(OAc)2 (5mol%) and PPh3 (20mol%) in THF (method A). Under these conditions the substitution of the bromine with hydrogen in 1a was complete at room temperature in less than 30min, giving the dehalogenated pyridine 2a in almost quantitative yield (entry 1, Table 1 ). Similar results were also obtained with (6-bromopyridin-2-yl)phenylmethanol 1b (entry 2, Table 1). The more sterically hindered bromide in pyridines 1c and 1d (entries 3 and 4, Table 1) was also removed quantitatively at room temperature, albeit after a somewhat extended reaction time (1.5 and 6h, respectively). These reaction conditions were unsatisfactory to hydrodehalogenate the meta-bromide in the pyridine 1e (entry 5, Table 1), and even increasing the amount of both the couple NaBH4-TMEDA (1.7–3.4) and catalyst (5–10mol%) (method B) only partial conversion was achieved. However, the reduction was successful when the reaction was carried out at 60°C under method A, giving the reduced product in good yield (83%). Impressively, this transformation could take place at room temperature when PdCl2(dppf) [dppf=1,1′-bis(diphenylphosphino)] was used as the catalyst. Thus, 5mol% PdCl2(dppf), NaBH4 (1.7equiv) and TMEDA (1.7equiv) (method C) converted 1e into the related hydrohalogenated pyridine 2e in excellent yield (95%) after 2h at room temperature. Under these reaction conditions also the meta-bromide in 3-bromo-5-phenylpyridine 1f was removed in good yield (85%) after 1.5h (entry 6). As expected, chloropyridines resulted less reactive than the related bromoheterocycles. Thus, for instance, chloropyridine 1g was unreactive under the conditions in which the related bromoropyridine 1d was smoothly reduced (entry 7 versus 4, Table 1), and only partial conversion was obtained when the reaction was carried out at 60°C for 72h. Fortunately, also in this case the use of PdCl2(dppf) was beneficial, allowing the pyridine 2d to be obtained in excellent yield (95%) after 6h. In this circumstance, to speed up the reaction 3.4equiv of the couple NaBH4-TMEDA (method D) were employed. The 2-chloropyridine 1h behaved as expected (entry 8, Table 1), whereas the meta-chloride in 5-chloro-2-phenylpyridine 1i failed to react under method D at room temperature, but it was converted into 2-phenylpyridine 2a by heating at 60°C for 2.5h with 1.7equiv NaBH4-TMEDA. 3.2 Hydrodehalogenation of halogenated quinolines and isoquinolines The removal of the bromine or chlorine from quinoline derivatives was obtained analogously to the related pyridines (Table 2 ). Hydrodehalogenation of reactive bromides was efficiently performed by Pd(OAc)2-PPh3, whereas PdCl2(dppf) was necessary for chlorides and bromides in unactivated positions of the heterocycle ring. For the hydrodehalogenation of 1-chloroisoquinoline method C was required, notwithstanding the chlorine is located in the very reactive 1-position of the isoquinoline ring (entry 8, Table 2). The removal of the 3-chlorine from 3-chloroisoquinoline 3i was more problematic even when the reaction was carried out at 60°C under method D (entry 9, Table 2), but by doubling the amount of PdCl2(dppf) (10mol%) a good yield (82%) was obtained. On the other hand, the 4-bromide in isoquinoline 3j was smoothly reduced by method D (entry 11, Table 2). 3.3 Hydrodehalogenation of halogenated pyrazines and pyrimidines Our protocol was next examined for the hydrodehalogenation of 6-membered heterocycles with two nitrogens (Table 3 ). Since the reactivity of the 2-chlorine in quinoxaline 5a is expected to be superior to that of the quinoline [6,46] (entry 4, Table 2), the reduction of 2-chloroquinoxaline was initially performed with method A at room temperature. Under these reaction conditions dechlorination occurred within 1h, affording quinoxaline 6a in 72% yield (entry 1, Table 3). An attempt to increase the yield by using PdCl2(dppf) (5mol%) as the catalyst was unsuccessful giving 6a in lower yield (52%). The 4-chlorine in 4-chloroquinazoline 5b resulted less reactive than that in 5a, requiring method D to be removed at the same reaction rate and more with a lower yield (58%) (entry 2, Table 3). On the other hand, hydrodechlorination of 4-chloro-2,6-dimethoxypyrimidine under method D occurred in high yield (92%), but with a longer reaction time (entry 3, Table 3). 3.4 Regioselective hydrodehalogenation of halogenated six-membered heterocycles with one or two heteroatoms On the basis of the above results, the regioselective hydrodehalogenation of a number of six- membered polyhalogenated heterocycles was examined (Table 4 ). The simple catalyst Pd(OAc)2-PPh3 was enough reactive to promote the selective removal in fairly good yield (68%) of the 2-bromine substituent in pyridines 1j, leaving unchanged the bromine in the 5-position (entry 1, Table 4). 4,7-Dichloroquinoline 3k was completely converted under PdCl2(dppf) catalysis (method D) after 6h at room temperature, giving the 7-chloroquinoline as the sole product in 95% yield (entry 2, Table 4). It should be noted that this result is the best one among the several methods pursued for this goal [6]. Method D was also able to reduce selectively the 2-chlorine in 2,8-dichloroquinoline 3l, but in this case the yield of the formed 8-dichloroquinoline 4f was lower (75%) (entry 3, Table 4). More problematic was the regioselective hydrodechlorination of 1,3-dichloroisoquinoline 3m. Method A after 11h reacting afforded the selective removal of the 1-chlorine, but 3-chlororoisoquinoline 3i was isolated in moderate yield (53%). More profitable was the use of PdCl2(dppf) (method C) by which 3i was formed in 71% yield with 9% of isoquinoline. The hydrodehalogenation of 2,4-dichloro-5-methoxypyrimidine gave a complex mixture from which 4-chloro-5-methoxypyrimidine was isolated in only 32% yield (entry 5, Table 4). 3.5 Chemoselective hydrodehalogenation of halogenated pyridines Next, the chemoselective reduction of a variety of functionalized halogenated pyridines was investigated. The reducing system showed high functional group tolerance, e.g., nitrile, amide, ester, alkyne and alkene substituents (Table 5 ). It should be noted than when (Z)-2-bromo-3-styrylpyridine 1p was submitted to hydrodebromination using Pd(OAc)2-PPh3 (5% and 20%, respectively) and NaBH4 (3.4equiv) and TMEDA (3.4equiv) (method E), the reduction of the 2-bromine occurred smoothly, but afforded in 84% overall yield a 3:1 mixture of two isomeric alkenes, (Z)- and (E)-3-styrylpyridine, by partial stereoinversion of the CC bond (entry 6, Table 5). The removal of a bromo atom from a pyridine containing a ketonic carbonyl group was also examined, notwithstanding the known ability of NaBH4 to reduce the carbonyl functionality. Surprisingly, the reaction of (6-bromopyridin-2-yl)(phenyl)methanone 1q under method A gave, by chemoselective removal of the 2-bromine, phenyl(pyridin-2-yl)methanone 2o in 74% yield (entry 7, Table 5). A similar result was also obtained in the reduction of the analogue 1-(6-bromopyridin-2-yl)ethanone 1r (entry 8, Table 5). In both cases, a variable amount (5-20%) of alcohols resulting from the reduction of the carbonyl moiety of either the starting material and the debrominated starting material was detected by 1H NMR. Thus, when a large excess of NaBH4 (3.4equiv) was added to the solution containing the crude phenyl(pyridin-2-yl)methanone 2o, formed by initial reduction of 1q under method A (entry 7, Table 5), (phenyl(pyridin-2-yl)methanol was isolated in 84% yield after a further 2h reaction time. Thus, this method appears to allow the one pot consecutive hydrodebromination and reduction of a pyridine ring containing a bromine and ketonic carbonyl group. Encouraged by these results, the hydrodehalogenation of a bromopyridine containing the very reactive formyl moiety was also examined. Unfortunately, when 2-bromopyridine-3-carboxaledehyde 1s was reacted under method A, the reduction of the carbonyl group to the related alcohol occurred rather than the removal of the bromine from the pyridine ring (entry 9, Table 5). 3.6 Hydrodehalogenation of halogenated five-membered heterocycles with one heteroatom The good results obtained in the hydrodehalogenation of halogenated 6-membered heterocycles prompted us to verify the potential of this system for the removal of halogens in less reactive heterocycles [6,46] as heteropentalenes with one or more heteroatoms (Table 6 ). To assess the reactivity of this kind of heterocycles the hydrodehalogenation of 2-bromo-5-phenylthiophene 7a was examined. Initial experiments were performed at room temperature with Pd(OAc)2 (5mol%) and PPh3 (20mol%) as the catalytic system and an excess of the couple NaBH4-TMEDA (1.7equiv) in THF (entry 1, Table 6). Under these reaction conditions the substitution of the bromine with hydrogen was incomplete after 24h. However, by doubling the amount of NaBH4-TMEDA (3.4equiv) (method E) complete conversion was achieved after 2h and the product, 2-phenylthiophene 8a, was isolated in 94% yield. Also when PdCl2(dppf) (5mol%) was used as the catalyst in combination with 1.7equiv of the reducing system, incomplete conversion occurred after 24h, but by using 3.4equiv NaBH4-TMEDA (method D) the reaction was complete in 1h and 8a was formed in 92% yield. Similarly, the 2-bromo substitute thiophenes 7b and 7c were efficiently hydrodehalogenated under method D. The known lower reactivity of the β-bromine in thiophene was evident since PdCl2(dppf) was necessary to remove this halide from the thiophene 7d (entry 4, Table 6). Method D was also able to remove the bromine from the sterically hindered 3-bromo substituted thiophenes 7f and 7g (entries 6 and 7, Table 6), but in these cases the reactions needed to be carried out at 65°C. Interestingly, with the polar thiophene 7g a better result was obtained when the reaction was carried out in acetonitrile instead of THF (86% versus 74% yield). The removal of the 2-bromine of benzothiophene 7h, 1-methylindole 7i and benzofuran 7j was performed efficiently (85–95 yields) with both methods E and D, with the second one affording a very short reaction time. The reduction of the furane derivative 7k failed to give the expected debrominated compound 8i (entry 11, Table 6), and an intractable reaction mixture was instead formed. The reduction of the 3-bromobenzothiophene 7l, was performed efficiently with method D at room temperature, though a shorter reaction time was obtained in similar yield by carrying out the reaction at 65°C. Heating and PdCl2(dppf) were instead imperative to remove the sterically hindered β-bromine in benzothiophene 7m (entry 13, Table 6). Finally, the reduction of the 3-bromo derivatives of 1-methylindole 7n and benzofuran 7o was performed efficiently with method D, affording the parent heterocycles in 93% and 64% yields, respectively. The removal of the chlorine from a thiophene and benzothiophene rings was also addressed. Initially, the reduction of 2-chloro-5-phenylthiophene 7p was examined since this goal had been achieved only in some well-defined cases [2b,48]. After several experiments with different catalytic systems we found that the hydrodehalogenation of 7p was more efficiently obtained by using 5mol% PdCl2(tbpf) [tbpf=1,1’-bis(di-tert-butylphosphino)ferrocene] at 65°C for 8h (96% yield) (entry 5, Table 7 ). On the other hand, the removal of the chlorine from 3-chlorobenzothiophene 7q under these and other reaction conditions failed (Table 8 ). The very low reactivity of this heteroaryl chloride is demonstrated by the fact that only very recently has been discovered that the combination of Pd(OAc)2 and XPhos (2-dicyclohexylphosphanyl-2′,4′,6′-triisopropylbiphenyl) was able to catalyze the Suzuki–Miyaura coupling of this substrate.[48] Inspired by this results we assessed this catalyst for our purpose. Unfortunately, also in this case no reaction occurred. 3.7 Regioselective hydrodehalogenation of halogenated five-membered heterocycles with one heteroatom On the basis of the above results, the regioselective hydrodehalogenation of some polyhalogenated heteropentalenes was examined (Table 9 ). The simple catalyst Pd(OAc)2-PPh3 (5% and 20%, respectively) was reactive enough to promote the selective removal with high yield of the 2-bromo substituent in dibrominated thiophenes 9a and 9b, benzothiophene 9c, N-methylindole 9d and N-methoxycarbonyl indole 9e, leaving unchanged the bromine in the other positions (entries 1–5, Table 9). Interestingly, by conducing the reduction of 9c under PdCl2(dppf) catalysis (method D) the same yield than with method E was obtained, but with the reaction times reduced to 50min. The reduction of 2,3-dibromobenzofuran was more complicated. Thus, PdCl2(dppf) and 1.7equiv of NaBH4-TMEDA gave only partial conversion, whereas by increasing the amount of the reducing system to 3.4equiv total conversion of the starting material was achieved after 45minutes, affording however a mixture of 3-Br-benzofuran 10f (56%) and benzofuran (31%). On the other hand, the monobromo derivative 10f, containing only traces of benzofuran, was obtained in 77% yield, by using 2.5equiv of NaBH4-TMEDA. Thanks to the results obtained in the reduction of 9c and 9f, the regioselective hydrodebromination of their tribromoderivative analogues, 2,3,6-tribromobenzo[b]thiophene 9g and 2,3,5-tribromobenzofuran 9h, was also examined. However, the regioselective reduction of these substrates was disappointing. Thus, with compound 9g the best result of 3,6-dibromobenzo[b]thiophene 10g (52% yield) was achieved under method C, though the conversion was only 77%. Increasing the amount of NaBH4-TMEDA to 2.5equiv, total conversion was obtained after 1h, but with a reduced yield of 10g (41%). Still less selective was the reduction of 9h that under the above reaction conditions afforded a mixture of products (determined by 1H NMR) containing only 44% of 10h. 3.8 Chemoselective hydrodehalogenation of halogenated five-membered heterocycles Next, the chemoselective reduction of some haloheteropentalenes was investigated. The results described in Table 10 show that the reducing system has high functional group tolerance, e.g., ester, alkyne, alkene and nitrile substituents (entries 1–5, Table 10). 3.9 Hydrodehalogenation of halogenated five-membered heterocycles with two heteroatoms In the series of the heteropentalenes with two heteroatoms, 2-bromo-4-phenylthiazole 11a was hydrodehalogenated efficiently by method E (entry 1, Table 11 ). Methods E and D were also successful in the reduction of the low reactive 2-chlorine in the thiazole 11b, but failed to remove the 5-chlorine from the thiazole 11c. On the other hand, this goal was efficiently achieved by the complex PdCl2(tbpf) that required in any case the heating at 65°C to afford complete conversion (entry 3, Table 11, method F). Method D resulted efficient in the removal of the 5- and 4-bromine from thiazoles 11d and 11e, but resulted relatively inactive in the reduction of 2-bromobenzo[d]thiazole 11f at room temperature. In this case the use of method E resulted more profitable. Unexpectedly, the removal of the chlorine in 2-chlorobenzo[d]thiazole 11g was more effectively obtained with method D (entry 7, Table 11). The bromine in imidazole derivatives 11h and 11i was obtained by Pd(OAc)2-PPh3, whereas PdCl2(dppf) was necessary to dechlorinate 2-chloro-1-(4-fluorobenzyl)-1H-benzo[d]imidazole 11k (entry 11, Table 11). 3-Bromoimidazo[1,2-a]pyridine 11j was quickly reduced by the simple method A. 3-Bromo-1-methyl-1H-indazole 11l was debrominated with both methods E and D, but the latter was more performing (entry 12, Table 11). Finally, in the reduction of 2-chlorobenzo[d]oxazole 11m and 4-bromo-3,5-dimethylisoxazole 11n, the disappearance of the starting material was observed after a short reaction time, but the formation of the expected benzo[d]oxazole 12h and 3,5-dimethylisoxazole 12i, respectively, was not detected (entries 13 and 14, Table 11). 3.10 Regioselective hydrodehalogenation of halogenated five-membered heterocycles with two heteroatoms The regioselective hydrodehalogenation of two polyhalogenated heteropentalenes with two heteroatoms, namely thiazoles and imidazoles, was studied (Table 12 ). The removal of the 2-chlorine from the dichlorinated heterocycles, 2-chloro-4-(4-chlorophenyl)thiazole 11o and 2,5-dichlorobenzo[d]thiazole 11p was possible with method D, although method E gave higher yield with the substrate 11p (entries 1 and 2, Table 12). The simple catalyst Pd(OAc)2-PPh3 (method E) was reactive enough to promote the selective removal with high yield of the 5-bromine substituent in 4,5-dibromo-2-phenylthiazole 11q (entry 3, Table 12). On the other hand, the hydrodebromination of 2,5-dibromo-4-phenylthiazole 11r was less satisfactory. With method E a mixture of 5-bromo-4-phenylthiazole 12l and 4-phenylthiazole 12a in a 90/10 ratio was obtained. When the reaction was carried out at 0°C total conversion required 14h and the 12l/12a ratio was increased up to 93/7. Several attempts to improve the selectivity by using different catalytic systems failed. Thus, for instance, the use of both Pd2(dba)3 (2.5mol%) and Pd(OAc)2 (5mol%) in combination with XantPhos (5mol%) at 25°C gave a mixture of 12l and 12a in high yield, but with a ratio of only 86/14. A similar result was obtained by carrying the reaction at 0°C. The selective removal of one of the two bromines in the reduction of 1-benzyl-4,5-dibromo-1H-imidazole 11s was practically impossible to achieve with this system despite a number of permutations of conditions have been pursued. By performing the reduction of 11s with both Pd(OAc)2-PPh3 and PdCl2(dppf) in combination of 3.4equiv NaBH4-TMEDA, a mixture of the monobromide 11i and completely debrominated imidazole 12d was recovered in a 3/1 ratio. When the amount of the reducing system was reduced to 1.7 and then to 1.1 under PdCl2(dppf) catalysis, the conversion of the starting material was uncompleted, but the 11i/12d ratio remained practically unchanged (2.9/1 ÷ 2.7/1)), indicating that the formation of 12d is independent from the conversion 11s into 11i. Finally, the hydrodebromination of the more demanding 1-benzyl-2,4,5-tribromoimidazole 11s was examined. Method E at room temperature gave a mixture of 1-benzyl-4,5-dibromoimidazole 11r and 1-benzyl-4-bromoimidazole 11i in a 63/37 ratio, containing also traces (<5%) of 1-benzylimidazole. Reducing the number of equivalents of the reductant from 3.4 to 2.5 increased only slightly the selectivity (11s/11i =76/24), whereas a further decrease to 1.7equiv gave only partial conversion of the starting material after 72h. After a series of optimization experiments, the combination of Pd2(dba)3 (2.5mol%) and XantPhos (5mol%) 3.4equiv of NaBH4-TMEDA at 0°C (method L) was found to produce with good yield 11s and 11i in a 87/13 ratio. 3.11 Chemoselective hydrodehalogenation of halogenated five-membered heterocycles with two heteroatoms In this circumstance, the selective removal of the bromine versus chlorine from thiazoles 13a and 13b was examined (Table 13 ). The reduction of 2-bromo-5-chloro-4-phenylthiazole 13a occurred smoothly and the 2-bromine was removed selectively to give 5-chloro-4-phenylthiazole 11c in 79% yield. The chemoselectivity in this case is due to two factors working cooperatively, namely the greater reactivity of the C–Br bond with respect the C–Cl bond (see for instance entry 1 versus 2 in Table 11) and the higher reactivity of the 2-position compared to the 5-position of the thiazole ring toward the metal insertion into C-halogen bonds (see for instance entries 1 and 2 versus 4 and 5 in Table 11). Such a situation is to be found in the hydrodehalogenation of 4-bromo-5-chloro-2-phenylthiazole 13b in which the 4-position appears to be favoured for both of the above reasons (see for instance entry 4 versus 5 in Table 11). However, the reduction of 13b failed unexpectedly under the reaction conditions (method D) that allowed the removal of the 4- and 5-bromine in thiazoles 11c and 11d (Table 11). By carrying out the reduction at 60°C partial conversion of 13b was observed, but none of the expected products was detected. The use of PdCl2(tbpf) that removes efficiently the 5-chlorine in 5-chloro-4-phenylthiazole 11c (entry 3, Table 11) was also unsuccessful. 3.12 Mechanism considerations The dehalogenation efficiency of NaBH4-TMEDA arises from the fact that the addition of a nitrogen-base, especially TMEDA, considerably enhances the performance of NaBH4 [16c]. On the base of the generally accepted mechanism based on oxidative addition, hydride transfer (transmetallation) and reductive elimination, the effect of TMEDA can be three-fold: (a) weak coordination to the electronically and coordinatively unsaturated intermediate in form of [Pd(ligand)(TMEDA)] thereby stabilizing the catalyst and minimizing catalyst decomposition. The weak donor ability of TMEDA ensures its cleavage upon entry of the substrate; (b) capture of BH3 from BH4 − provides an extra drive for hydride transfer to the Pd centre (ArBr+NaBH4 +1/2TMEDA→ArH+NaBr+1/2TMEDA•2BH3). The resultant TMEDA•2BH3 adduct could also serve as an additional hydride source [49]; (c) alternative debromination pathway through the elimination of HBr. 4 Conclusions In conclusion, the pair NaBH4-TMEDA as hydride source and a palladium catalyst in THF prove to be an efficient system for the hydrodehalogenation of halogenated heterocycles with one or more heteroatoms. Since in the heterocycles the reactivity of the C-halogen bonds varies significantly from one substrate to another, the rates and yields of the dehalogenation depend critically on the type of halide (Br>Cl) and on the choice of the catalyst, amount of the pair NaBH4-TMEDA and temperature. In general, the simple and inexpensive catalyst Pd(OAc)2-PPh3 rapidly hydrodehalogenates reactive halo-heterocycles such as bromo-pyridines, -quinolines, -thiophenes, -indoles, -imidazoles, etc., at room temperature in very good yields, whereas in most cases PdCl2(dppf) reduces less reactive halides such as chloro-pyridines, -quinolines, -pyrimidines and bromo-indoles, -benzofurans, etc. Moreover, PdCl2(tbpf) shows to be even more active removing the 2- and 5-chlorine from both thiophene and thiazole rings, respectively, which are rather sluggish with other reagents. The reaction conditions tolerate various functional groups, allowing highly chemoselective reactions in the presence of halide, ester, alkyne, alkene and nitrile substituents. Moreover, with a proper selection of the catalyst it is also possible to obtain a good control in the regioselective hydrodehalogenation of a variety of polyhalogenated substrates. The practical and selective methodology offers a very powerful, low-cost and safe way for the hydrodehalogenation of halogenated heteroaromatics and may constitute a key step in the synthesis of complex molecules. coredata.dc:description: The pair NaBH4-TMEDA as hydride source and a palladium catalyst in THF prove to be an efficient system for the hydrodehalogenation of halogenated heterocycles with one or more heteroatoms. In general, Pd(OAc)2-PPh3 rapidly hydrodehalogenates reactive halo-heterocycles such as bromo-pyridines, -quinolines, -thiophenes, -indoles, -imidazoles, etc., at room temperature in very good yields, whereas in most cases PdCl2(dppf) reduces less reactive halides such as chloro-pyridines, -quinolines, -pyrimidines and bromo-indoles, -benzofurans, etc. Moreover, PdCl2(tbpf) shows to be even more active removing the 2- and 5-chlorine from both thiophene and thiazole rings. The reaction conditions tolerate various functional groups, allowing highly chemoselective reactions in the presence of halide, ester, alkyne, alkene and nitrile substituents. Moreover, with a proper selection of the catalyst it is also possible to obtain a good control in the regioselective hydrodehalogenation of a variety of polyhalogenated substrates.
coredata.dc:title: NaBH4-TMEDA and a palladium catalyst as efficient regio- and chemoselective system for the hydrodehalogenation of halogenated heterocycles
